docs {
  # Order Flow (E2E)

  A single, self-contained, top-to-bottom run that sets up a system **from
  scratch** and creates a **complete order** ‚Äî Business Login ‚Üí catalogue ‚Üí branch
  import ‚Üí **provision an order-capable user** ‚Üí **log in as that user** ‚Üí master
  records ‚Üí patient ‚Üí **Create Order** ‚Äî with each request feeding the ids it
  captured into the next. Select the **Local** environment and **Run Folder** (or
  run each request in `seq` order); no manual edits are needed.

  The payoff: after the run you can copy the new user's credentials
  (`orderUserIdentifier` + `orderUserPassword`), log into the business frontend,
  and reproduce the whole Create-Order flow in the UI.

  ## Fully automated ‚Äî just click Send

  Every request has a `script:post-response` that extracts the ids it produces and
  stores them as **runtime variables** via `bru.setVar(...)`; every dependent
  request reads them via `{{...}}`. Runtime vars live for the duration of the run,
  so no values are written back to the `Local` environment file. There are **no
  hardcoded ids** ‚Äî the only seeded values are the admin login creds and
  `orderUserPassword` in the `Local` environment. Auto-captured variables:

  `businessAccessToken`, `businessRefreshToken`, `tenantId`, `branchId`,
  `departmentId`, `departmentShortName`, `categoryId`, `subCategoryId`,
  `masterDataId`, `labTestId`, `labPanelId`, `branchLabTestId`,
  `branchLabPanelId`, `orderUserId`, `orderUserIdentifier`, `orderUserCode`,
  `consultantDoctorId`, `labAdministratorId`, `phlebotomistId`, `radiologistId`,
  `radiologyTechnicianId`, `patientId`, `medicalHistoryId`, `orderId`, `paymentId`.

  `branchId` is derived from the **JWT** (decoded in steps 1, 3 and 18), so the
  whole chain always targets the branch your token is actually scoped to ‚Äî this is
  what keeps the branch import (steps 10-13) consistent with the catalogue
  (steps 7-9) and with the order-capable user's branch.

  ## The 26 steps

  1-3   **Auth + branch** ‚Äî admin login, resolve main branch, switch to a
        branch-scoped token.
  4-9   **Catalogue** ‚Äî Department, Category, Sub-Category, then master-data Lab
        Test and Lab Panel.
  10-13 **Branch import + verify** ‚Äî import the parent Lab Test and Lab Panel into
        the branch, then **list them to verify the import** (also capturing the
        `branchLabTestId` / `branchLabPanelId` the order uses).
  14-18 **Order-Capable User** ‚Äî enable the Registration + Sales modules on the
        branch, create a receptionist user, assign the branch/role/modules, grant
        the registration + sales permissions, then **log in as that user**.
  19-23 **Staff master data** ‚Äî Consultant Doctor, Lab Administrator (a REPORTING
        doctor), Phlebotomist, Radiologist, and pick a Radiology Technician.
  24-25 **Patient + Order** ‚Äî register the patient and create the complete order.
  26    **Verify** ‚Äî re-fetch the composed order.

  ## The pivot: steps 14-18 (Order-Capable User)

  All requests authenticate with `Bearer {{businessAccessToken}}`. Steps 1-17 use
  the **admin** token (catalogue + branch config are admin work). **Step 18 logs
  in as the new receptionist and OVERWRITES `businessAccessToken`**, so every step
  from 19 on runs as that user ‚Äî which is exactly what proves a freshly-provisioned
  order-capable user can create the order (not just an all-powerful admin).

  The user is a `receptionist` with the **Registration** + **Sales** modules
  enabled at the branch and the matching `registration:*` / `sales:*` permissions
  granted. Business order routes aren't RBAC-gated server-side yet, so those grants
  mainly drive **frontend module visibility** (a module stays hidden in the FE
  unless the user is enabled + permissioned for it).

  ## Reproduce in the frontend

  After a green run, copy `orderUserIdentifier` + `orderUserPassword` from the
  `Local` environment into the business frontend login. The Registration module
  will be visible and you can create an order in the UI ‚Äî the same order this flow
  creates via the API.

  ## Prerequisites

  - The backend is running (`pnpm start:dev` in `kalnostics-new/`) with Postgres
    and a **seeded tenant** that has a main branch and a business admin whose login
    creds are in the `Local` environment (`adminPhone` / `adminTempPassword`).
  - Several branch-level steps (import, module config, branch-scoped order) require
    the JWT to carry an **active branch**. A plain `business_admin` login is
    tenant-level (`active_branch_id: null`), so **step 3 (Switch to Branch
    Profile)** re-issues a branch-scoped token. That switch only succeeds if the
    login user holds a branch-level profile at the branch ‚Äî see that request's docs
    if it 403s.

  ## Re-run note

  The fixed `E2E` identifiers ‚Äî the user's `username`/`email`/`mobileNumber`
  (step 15), each doctor's `registrationNo` (steps 19-20), the department
  `shortName` (step 4), and the patient `mobile` (step 24) ‚Äî are unique keys, so a
  second run against the same DB returns 409 conflicts. Reset the DB (or bump those
  values) before re-running.

  Full CRUD (List / Update / Delete) for orders lives in **42 Orders**.
}
